  "prompt": "What is the square root of 40 in radical form?",
  "response": "The square root of 40 in radical form is \\(\\sqrt{40}\\). This can be simplified by factoring 40 into its prime factors:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{4 \\times 10} = \\sqrt{4 \\times (2 \\times 5)} \\]\n\nSince 4 is a perfect square, it can be simplified further:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt{40} = \\sqrt{4} \\times \\sqrt{10} = 2\\sqrt{10} \\]\n\nSo, the square root of 40 in its simplest radical form is \\(2\\sqrt{10}\\).",
